3zv.title: Logarithm tutorial overview
3zv.text:
[summary: The logarithm tutorial covers the following six subjects: 1. What are logarithms? 2. Logarithms as a measure of length. 3. Logarithms as a measure of data and information. 4. Why do logarithms make some calculations more efficient? 5. Logarithms vs exponentials. 6. There is only one logarithm.] The following topics are covered in the [3wj Arbital logarithm tutorial]: ## 1. Definition of the logarithm Logarithms are a type of [3jy] from numbers to numbers. There is a logarithm function for every positive number $b$ [log_base_1 except 1], and the function for $b$, called "the logarithm base $b$" or just "log base $b$", takes an input $x$ and counts how many times you have to multiply $1$ by $b$ to get $x$. For example, the log base 10 of 1000 is 3, because you have to multiply 1 by 10 three times to get 1000; and the log base 2 of 16 is 4, because you have to multiply 1 by 2 four times to get 16. The log base $b$ of $x$ is written $\log_b(x).$ Here's a graph of part of log base 2: ![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Binary_logarithm_plot_with_ticks.svg/408px-Binary_logarithm_plot_with_ticks.svg.png "By Krishnavedala. Own work, CC BY-SA 3.0, goo.gl/VzKMzu") This tutorial explores how logarithms work, and builds intuition for what they actually do. ## 2. Log as length Logarithms measure how long a number is, for a specific notion of "length" where fractional lengths are allowed. For example, the number 139 is three digits long: $$\underbrace{139}_\text{3 digits}$$ And the logarithm (base 10) of 139 is pretty close to 3. In fact, it's closer to 2 than it is to 3, because 139 is closer to 99 than it is to 999. Specifically, $\log_{10}(139) \approx 2.14$. We can interpret this as saying "139 is three digits long in [decimal_notation], and it's closer to being a 2 digit number than it is to being a 3 digit number." I don't know what $\log_{10}(\text{2,310,426})$ is, but I can immediately tell you that it's between 6 and 7, and closer to 6, because it takes 7 digits to write 2,310,426, and it's small for a 7-digit number. $$\underbrace{\text{2,310,426}}_\text{7 digits}$$ Why are the logarithms above using base 10? What does it mean to say that a number is "two and a half digits long"? Why is it 316 (rather than 500) that is using two and a half digits? These questions and others are answered in the tutorial. ## 3. Logs measure data Logarithms measure how hard it is to represent messages using physical objects in the world. Let's say that we're magicians, and I want to tell you what card I'm thinking of by using sleight-of-hand to arrange some dice. How many 6-sided dice do I need to set (without the audience noticing) to send you a message that tells you which card I'm thinking of, assuming there are 52 possibilities? At least $\log_6(52).$ Why? The answer reveals a link between logarithms are the "data capacity" of physical objects. ## 4. Life in log-space Empirically, logarithms have proved quite a useful tool for people and machines who have to do lots and lots of multiplications. Scientists and engineers used to use giant pre-computed tables of the logs of common numbers, and use those to make their calculations. Today, many modern learning algorithms (and AI algorithms, such as [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AlphaGo AlphaGo]) manipulate the logs of probabilities instead of manipulating probabilities directly. Why? This tutorial spends some time exploring when and why it is easier to deal with the logarithms of things than it is to deal with the things themselves. ## 5. Logarithms and exponentials People are often introduced to logarithms by being told that they are the inverse of [exponential exponentials]. Any time you find two collections of things where the first set multiplies every time the second set grows by one unit, exponentials and logarithms are the mathematical tools that describe the relationship between those sets. For example, if the amount of bacteria in a culture multiplies every time a day passes, then logarithms measure days in terms of bacteria, and exponentials measure bacteria in terms of days. In general, logarithms tell you what happens to the second set when the first set changes a little; exponentials tell you what happens to the first set when the second set changes a little. This relationship between logarithms and exponentials is worth exploring, given the prevalence of logarithmic/exponential processes in the world. ## 6. There is only one logarithm While there are many logarithm functions (one for each positive number except 1), there is a sense in which they're all the same. This tutorial concludes by exploring this idea, and exploring the similarities shared by all logarithm functions.
---
These six concepts are nowhere near all there is to say on the topic of logarithms. Logarithms have applications to many domains, including physics, computer science, calculus, number theory, and psychology (to name a few). Logarithms are easy to [derivative derive] and [integral integrate]; the number of prime numbers less than $x$ is roughly $\frac{x}{\log_e(x)}$; efficient search algorithms can run in a time logarithmic in the number of things to search through; and the human brain encodes many perceptions logarithmically — the tone you perceive when your ear processes vibrations in the air is the log base 2 of the frequency. These facts, and concepts such as [complex_logarithm complex logarithms], are not covered in this tutorial. Instead, the focus of the tutorial is on building a solid intuition for what the logarithm does, and why it has its most important properties. To dive in, click the button below! (TODO)
